  abstract = {The \${\textbackslash}ell\_p\$-norm regression problem is a classic problem in optimization with wide ranging applications in machine learning and theoretical computer science. The goal is to compute \$x\^{}\{{\textbackslash}star\} ={\textbackslash}arg{\textbackslash}min\_\{Ax=b\}{\textbackslash}{\textbar}x{\textbackslash}{\textbar}\_p\^{}p\$, where \$x\^{}\{{\textbackslash}star\}{\textbackslash}in {\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}\^{}n, A{\textbackslash}in {\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}\^{}\{d{\textbackslash}times n\},b {\textbackslash}in {\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}\^{}d\$ and \$d{\textbackslash}leq n\$. Efficient high-accuracy algorithms for the problem have been challenging both in theory and practice and the state of the art algorithms require \$poly(p){\textbackslash}cdot n\^{}\{{\textbackslash}frac\{1\}\{2\}-{\textbackslash}frac\{1\}\{p\}\}\$ linear system solves for \$p{\textbackslash}geq 2\$. In this paper, we provide new algorithms for \${\textbackslash}ell\_p\$-regression (and a more general formulation of the problem) that obtain a high-accuracy solution in \$O(p n\^{}\{{\textbackslash}frac\{(p-2)\}\{(3p-2)\}\})\$ linear system solves. We further propose a new inverse maintenance procedure that speeds-up our algorithm to \${\textbackslash}widetilde\{O\}(n\^{}\{{\textbackslash}omega\})\$ total runtime, where \$O(n\^{}\{{\textbackslash}omega\})\$ denotes the running time for multiplying \$n {\textbackslash}times n\$ matrices. Additionally, we give the first Iteratively Reweighted Least Squares (IRLS) algorithm that is guaranteed to converge to an optimum in a few iterations. Our IRLS algorithm has shown exceptional practical performance, beating the currently available implementations in MATLAB/CVX by 10-50x.},
