  abstract = {On the space of positive definite matrices we consider distance functions of the form \$d(A,B)={\textbackslash}left[{\textbackslash}tr{\textbackslash}mathcal\{A\}(A,B)-{\textbackslash}tr{\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B){\textbackslash}right]\^{}\{1/2\},\$ where \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{A\}(A,B)\$ is the arithmetic mean and \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B)\$ is one of the different versions of the geometric mean. When \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B)=A\^{}\{1/2\}B\^{}\{1/2\}\$ this distance is \${\textbackslash}{\textbar}A\^{}\{1/2\}-B\^{}\{1/2\}{\textbackslash}{\textbar}\_2,\$ and when \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B)=(A\^{}\{1/2\}BA\^{}\{1/2\})\^{}\{1/2\}\$ it is the Bures-Wasserstein metric. We study two other cases: \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B)=A\^{}\{1/2\}(A\^{}\{-1/2\}BA\^{}\{-1/2\})\^{}\{1/2\}A\^{}\{1/2\},\$ the Pusz-Woronowicz geometric mean, and \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{G\}(A,B)={\textbackslash}exp{\textbackslash}big({\textbackslash}frac\{{\textbackslash}log A+{\textbackslash}log B\}\{2\}{\textbackslash}big),\$ the log Euclidean mean. With these choices \$d(A,B)\$ is no longer a metric, but it turns out that \$d\^{}2(A,B)\$ is a divergence. We establish some (strict) convexity properties of these divergences. We obtain characterisations of barycentres of \$m\$ positive definite matrices with respect to these distance measures.},
