  year = {2020},
  abstract = {In this report, we design a fast approximate ridge leverage score sampling algorithm for kernel matrices. Our algorithm achieves state-of-the-art time complexity while it processes data in a sequential way such that only one single pass of the data stream is needed. The algorithm builds upon the work SQUEAK [3], which is a sequential and distributed method for leverage score sampling and passes over the dataset only once. SQUEAK splits the dataset into subsets, calculates approximate scores in each set, and merges them to provide the score of the original dataset. The time complexity of SQUEAK scales with the number of data points n, which is worse than the recently proposed state-of-the-art algorithm BLESS [8], whose complexity only depends on n and the (ridge) effective dimension deff ({$\lambda$}, K ) for {$\lambda$}{\textsurd} the kernel matrix K (when {$\lambda$} is set to be O( n) for optimal learning guarantee). BLESS requires multiple passes of the data, however. Our algorithm combines the idea of SQUEAK and BLESS. We add a pre-processing step to each data subset ahead of the merging step in the SQUEAK algorithm. This step enables SQUEAK to achieve the same state-of-the-art complexity as BLESS, if the information of the effective dimension deff ({$\lambda$}, K ) is used for data splitting. We also provide a variant of the merging step in SQUEAK, resulting in a new algorithm that has comparable performance. Our numerical experiments on MNIST demonstrate the faster speed of the algorithm proposed in this report compared to BLESS and SQUEAK.},
