  abstract = {We describe LNLQ for solving the least-norm problem min {\textbardbl}{$x$}{\textbardbl} {\textbardbl} x {\textbardbl}  subject to {$Ax$}={$b$} A x = b , using the Golub--Kahan bidiagonalization of [{$b~A$}] [ b ~ A ] . Craig's method is known to be equivalent to applying the conjugate gradient method to the normal equations of the second kind ({$AATy$}={$b$} A A T y = b , {$x$}={$ATy$} x = A T y ); LNLQ is equivalent to applying SYMMLQ. If an underestimate of the smallest singular value is available, error upper bounds for both {$x$} x  and {$y$} y  are available cheaply at each iteration. LNLQ is a companion method to the least-squares solver LSLQ [R. Estrin, D. Orban, and M. A. Saunders, SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl., 40 (2019b), pp. 235--253] which is equivalent to SYMMLQ on the conventional normal equations. We show that the error bounds are tight and comparable to the bounds suggested by Arioli [SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl., 34 (2013), pp. 571--592] for CRAIG. A sliding window technique allows us to tighten the error bound for {$y$} y  at the expense of a few additional scalar operations per iteration. We illustrate the tightness of the error bounds on two standard test problems and on the computation of an inexact gradient in the context of a penalty method for PDE-constrained optimization.},
