  abstract = {Have you ever wanted to multiply an n {\texttimes} d matrix X, with n d, on the left by an m {\texttimes} n matrix G{\texttildelow} of i.i.d. Gaussian random variables, but could not afford to do it because it was too slow? In this work we propose a new randomized m {\texttimes} n matrix T , for which one can compute T {$\cdot$} X in only O(nnz(X)) + O{\texttildelow}(m2 {$\cdot$} d3) time, for which the total variation distance between the distributions T {$\cdot$} X and G{\texttildelow} {$\cdot$} X is as small as desired, i.e., less than any positive constant. Here nnz(X) denotes the number of non-zero entries of X. Assuming nnz(X) m2 {$\cdot$} d3, this is a significant savings over the na{\textasciidieresis}{\i}ve O(nnz(X)m) time to compute G{\texttildelow} {$\cdot$} X. Moreover, since the total variation distance is small, we can provably use T {$\cdot$} X in place of G{\texttildelow} {$\cdot$} X in any application and have the same guarantees as if we were using G{\texttildelow} {$\cdot$} X, up to a small positive constant in error probability. We apply this transform to nonnegative matrix factorization (NMF) and support vector machines (SVM).},
