  abstract = {We describe two algorithms to efficiently solve regularized linear least squares systems based on sketching. The algorithms compute preconditioners for \${\textbackslash}min {\textbackslash}{\textbar}Ax-b{\textbackslash}{\textbar}\^{}2\_2 + {\textbackslash}lambda {\textbackslash}{\textbar}x{\textbackslash}{\textbar}\^{}2\_2\$, where \$A{\textbackslash}in{\textbackslash}mathbb\{R\}\^{}\{m{\textbackslash}times n\}\$ and \${\textbackslash}lambda{$>$}0\$ is a regularization parameter, such that LSQR converges in \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}({\textbackslash}log(1/{\textbackslash}epsilon))\$ iterations for \${\textbackslash}epsilon\$ accuracy. We focus on the context where the optimal regularization parameter is unknown, and the system must be solved for a number of parameters \${\textbackslash}lambda\$. Our algorithms are applicable in both the underdetermined \$m{\textbackslash}ll n\$ and the overdetermined \$m{\textbackslash}gg n\$ setting. Firstly, we propose a Cholesky-based sketch-to-precondition algorithm that uses a `partly exact' sketch, and only requires one sketch for a set of \$N\$ regularization parameters \${\textbackslash}lambda\$. The complexity of solving for \$N\$ parameters is \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}(mn{\textbackslash}log({\textbackslash}max(m,n)) +N({\textbackslash}min(m,n)\^{}3 + mn{\textbackslash}log(1/{\textbackslash}epsilon)))\$. Secondly, we introduce an algorithm that uses a sketch of size \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}({\textbackslash}text\{sd\}\_\{{\textbackslash}lambda\}(A))\$ for the case where the statistical dimension \${\textbackslash}text\{sd\}\_\{{\textbackslash}lambda\}(A){\textbackslash}ll{\textbackslash}min(m,n)\$. The scheme we propose does not require the computation of the Gram matrix, resulting in a more stable scheme than existing algorithms in this context. We can solve for \$N\$ values of \${\textbackslash}lambda\_i\$ in \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}(mn{\textbackslash}log({\textbackslash}max(m,n)) + {\textbackslash}min(m,n){\textbackslash},{\textbackslash}text\{sd\}\_\{{\textbackslash}min{\textbackslash}lambda\_i\}(A)\^{}2 + Nmn{\textbackslash}log(1/{\textbackslash}epsilon))\$ operations.},
